In Java, the keyword is used to refer to the current object instance of the class. It
can be used to prefix any instance variable or method. It is particularly useful as a way of
differentiating between instance variables and local variables that may have the same name.
The keyword is optional unless ambiguity exists, such as needing to differentiate
between an instance variable and a parameter variable.
In Python, the keyword performs the task of referring to the current object instance
of the class. The keyword is mandatory to prefix an instance variable or method.
Additionally, must be listed as the first parameter for all methods belonging to the class.
When calling these methods in your code, you do not need to pass anything for that value;
Python will do it for you.

When naming your classes, it is standard practice to use a singular noun that represents the entity
the template represents. The methods (or functions) within that class should then be named as
verbs, indicating the action they will perform on the objects of the class.
In addition, the naming convention dictates the following for upper- and lower-casing of names:
Camel case in Java (e.g. myObject) and snake case in Python
Camel case in Java (e.g. calculateTotal) and snake case in Python
Camel case in Java and snake case in Python.
